|<>|  𝐀𝐫𝐫𝐚𝐲𝐬  |<>|
      >> Java array is a data structure that store data of the same type in a sequencial manner.
      >> Arrays are fixed in size. You cannot add or remove elements once an array is created.
      >> Arrays store elements contiguously in memory, ensuring fast access.
      >> Use "java.util.ArrayList" if you need a resizable array.

|><| 𝐓𝐲𝐩𝐞𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐀𝐫𝐫𝐚𝐲𝐬 𝐢𝐧 𝐉𝐚𝐯𝐚 |><|

  𝚂𝚒𝚗𝚐𝚕𝚎-𝙳𝚒𝚖𝚎𝚗𝚜𝚒𝚘𝚗𝚊𝚕 𝙰𝚛𝚛𝚊𝚢 :- A linear list of elements.
  𝙼𝚞𝚕𝚝𝚒-𝙳𝚒𝚖𝚎𝚗𝚜𝚒𝚘𝚗𝚊𝚕 𝙰𝚛𝚛𝚊𝚢 :- Arrays with more than one dimension (e.g., 2D or 3D arrays).

𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎  ::--

  class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Declare and initialize an array
        int[] numbers = new int[5];

        // Assign values
        numbers[0] = 10;
        numbers[1] = 20;
        numbers[2] = 30;
        numbers[3] = 40;
        numbers[4] = 50;

        // Access and print elements
        for (int i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {
            System.out.println(numbers[i]);
        }
    }
}

-------------------><-------------------><--------------------

𝙁𝙤𝙧-𝙀𝙖𝙘𝙝 𝙇𝙤𝙤𝙥 :::---
     >> It is used to iterate over arrays or collections of elements one by one.
     >> It is also called enhanced for Loop.
  
   Syntax ;;; 
     for (dataType element : arrayOrCollection) {
       // Code to be executed
       }

   For Example ;;;
      int[] array = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
      for (int num : array) {
       System.out.println(num);
      }

